  "title": "Energy of Simple Harmonic Motion",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Force in SHM",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Force in SHM</strong></h3><p>In the above article we found that the acceleration of a body in SHM is $\\text{a}=-{{\\omega }^{2}}\\text{x}$. Applying the equation of motion $\\mathbf{\\vec{F}}=\\text{m}\\mathbf{\\vec{a}}$, we have,</p><p>$F=-m{{\\omega }^{2}}x=-kx$</p><p>where,</p><p>$\\omega =\\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{k}}{\\text{m}}}$</p><p>Thus <strong>, in SHM the force is proportional and opposite to the displacement.&nbsp;</strong></p><p>That is when the displacement is to the right (positive) the force points to the left, and when the displacement is to the left (negative) the force points to the right. Thus, the force is always pointing toward the origin O. Such type of force appears when an elastic body such as a spring is deformed. That is why the constant $\\text{k}=\\text{m}{{\\omega }^{2}}$ is sometimes called the elastic constant. Further, since</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} \\omega =\\frac{2\\pi }{\\text{T}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{k}}{\\text{m}}} \\\\ \\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ T}=2\\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{m}}{\\text{k}}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ and, }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ f}=\\frac{1}{2\\pi }\\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{k}}{\\text{m}}} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db98c03b9dcaf1afe28d"
    },
    {
      "title": "Kinetic Energy in SHM",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Kinetic Energy in SHM</strong></h3><p>The kinetic energy of the particle is,</p><p>$\\text{K}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{m}{{\\text{v}}^{2}}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}{{\\text{A}}^{2}}\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{2}}\\left( \\omega \\text{t}+\\phi \\right)$</p><p>Since,</p><p>$\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{2}}\\theta =1-\\text{co}{{\\text{s}}^{2}}\\theta $</p><p>and using $\\text{x}=\\text{Acos}\\left( \\omega \\text{t}+\\phi \\right)$ for the displacement, we can also express the kinetic energy as,</p><p>$\\text{K}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}{{\\omega }^{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{A}}^{2}}\\left[ 1-\\text{co}{{\\text{s}}^{2}}\\left( \\omega \\text{t}+\\phi \\right) \\right]$</p><p>which can be written as,</p><p>$\\text{K}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}{{\\omega }^{2}}\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{A}}^{2}}-{{\\text{x}}^{2}} \\right)=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{k}\\left( {{\\text{A}}^{2}}-{{\\text{x}}^{2}} \\right)$</p><p>From this expression we can see that, the kinetic is maximum at the centre $\\left( \\text{x}=0 \\right)$ and zero at the extremes of oscillation $\\left( \\text{x}=\\pm \\text{A} \\right)$.</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db98c03b9dcaf1afe28e"
    },
    {
      "title": "Potential Energy in SHM",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Potential Energy in SHM</strong></h3><p>To obtain the potential energy we use the relation,</p><p>\\(\\mathrm{F}=-\\frac{\\mathrm{d} U}{\\mathrm{dx}}\\) or \\(\\frac{\\mathrm{d} U}{\\mathrm{dx}}=\\mathrm{kx~} (\\text{as } \\mathrm{F}=-\\mathrm{kx})\\)</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\therefore &amp; \\mathop{\\int }_{0}^{\\text{U}}\\text{d}U=\\mathop{\\int }_{0}^{\\text{x}}\\text{kxdx} \\\\ \\therefore &amp; \\text{U}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{k}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}{{\\omega }^{2}}{{\\text{x}}^{2}} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Thus, the potential energy has a minimum value at the centre $\\left( \\text{x}=0 \\right)$ and increases as the particle approaches either extreme of the oscillation $\\left( x=\\pm A \\right)$.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db98c03b9dcaf1afe28f"
    },
    {
      "title": "Total Energy in SHM",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Total Energy in SHM</strong></h3><p>Total energy can be obtained by adding potential and kinetic energies. Therefore,</p><p>$\\mathrm{K}=\\mathrm{K}+\\mathrm{U}=\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{~m} \\omega^2\\left(\\mathrm{~A}^2-\\mathrm{x}^2\\right)+\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{~m} \\omega^2 \\mathrm{x}^2$</p><p>$=\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{~m} \\omega^2 \\mathrm{~A}^2$</p><p>or $\\mathrm{E}=\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{kA}^2$ $\\left( \\text{ as } \\text{ m}{{\\omega }^{2}}=\\text{k} \\right)$</p><p>Which is a <strong>constant </strong>quantity. This was to be expected since the force is conservative.</p><p>Therefore, we may conclude that, during an oscillation, there is a continuous exchange of kinetic and potential energies. While moving away from the equilibrium position, the potential energy increases at the expense of the kinetic energy. When the particle moves towards the equilibrium position, the reserve happens.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"291\" height=\"183\"></p><p>Figure shows the variation of total energy (E), potential energy (U) and kinetic energy (K) with displacement (x).</p>",
      "position": 3,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db98c03b9dcaf1afe290"
    }
  ],
